#compdef swarm-cronjob
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# swarm-cronjob — declarative cron scheduler for Docker Swarm services:
#                 polls the Swarm daemon for services labeled with
#                 `swarm.cronjob.schedule=<cron-expression>` and re-deploys
#                 each one whenever its expression fires (Go, 873★)
#
# upstream: https://github.com/crazy-max/swarm-cronjob
# author : CrazyMax (the prolific Docker tooling author behind
#          docker-actions-toolkit, dockge-actions, ftpgrab, and many
#          other crazy-max/* infrastructure CLIs)
# license: MIT
#
# Source-direct completion: every flag below is verbatim from
# internal/model/cli.go on the crazy-max/swarm-cronjob tip — the
# alecthomas/kong `kong:"name='...',env='...',default='...',help='...'"`
# struct-tag annotations parsed exactly as declared on the Cli struct,
# preserving env-var bindings (LOG_LEVEL / LOG_JSON) and default values.
# swarm-cronjob is a daemon with no CLI subcommands — the cron schedule
# behavior is configured via Docker Swarm service LABELS on the services
# themselves, not via CLI flags, so the user-facing CLI surface is
# intentionally minimal.
#
# Direct deps from go.mod (selected):
#   github.com/robfig/cron/v3      v3.0.1   ← canonical Go cron-
#                                              expression scheduler
#                                              library (this axis) —
#                                              by Rob Figueiredo
#                                              (robfig/cron); the de-
#                                              facto standard "cron in
#                                              Go" with classic 5-field
#                                              syntax + Quartz-style
#                                              6-field (with seconds)
#                                              + descriptors (@daily /
#                                              @hourly / @reboot) +
#                                              the cron.Schedule
#                                              interface for custom
#                                              triggers + timezone-
#                                              aware parsing.  THE Go
#                                              answer to "run this
#                                              function on a recurring
#                                              schedule" — used by
#                                              Kubernetes' CronJob
#                                              controller (the source
#                                              of the cluster-side
#                                              cron behavior every K8s
#                                              user takes for
#                                              granted), Argo CD,
#                                              Caddy's reload-on-cert-
#                                              expire hooks, every Go
#                                              background-job library
#                                              (gocron, asynq's
#                                              recurring tasks, gocron-
#                                              x/gocron), and the
#                                              broader Go ecosystem.
#                                              The v3 API change from
#                                              v2 dropped the
#                                              singleton scheduler in
#                                              favor of explicit
#                                              `cron.New()` + per-job
#                                              schedule strings, which
#                                              is the API every modern
#                                              Go consumer uses.  swarm-
#                                              cronjob uses it in
#                                              internal/app/scheduler.go
#                                              — service labels carry
#                                              the cron expression, and
#                                              the daemon registers
#                                              each label-derived
#                                              schedule against a
#                                              `cron.Cron` instance
#                                              that re-deploys the
#                                              target service when
#                                              the expression fires.
#   github.com/docker/docker                  (Docker Engine / Swarm
#                                              API client — lists
#                                              services, watches label
#                                              changes, triggers
#                                              `ServiceUpdate` to
#                                              re-deploy on schedule)
#   github.com/alecthomas/kong                (CLI parser — struct-
#                                              tag-driven flag
#                                              registration, replaces
#                                              the older urfave/cli
#                                              the v1 codebase used)
#   github.com/rs/zerolog                     (structured logging —
#                                              JSON-or-text via
#                                              --log-json)
#   github.com/pkg/errors                     (error wrapping for
#                                              causality preservation)
#
# swarm-cronjob is a daemon that runs alongside your Docker Swarm
# cluster (typically as a Swarm-managed service itself, on a manager
# node).  At startup it queries the Swarm API for all services, scans
# their labels for `swarm.cronjob.enable=true` + `swarm.cronjob.schedule
# =<cron-expression>` (+ optional `swarm.cronjob.skip-running=true`),
# and registers a cron job per matching service.  Each fire triggers
# a service-update API call that increments the service's spec
# version, causing Swarm to re-schedule the task on a fresh container
# (effectively "re-run" the service).  Combined with `restart-condition:
# none` in the service spec, this lets you express "run this job once,
# every day at 03:00" purely via service labels, no external scheduler
# required.  Label-driven configuration means the cron schedule
# follows the service through `docker stack deploy` updates without
# touching the swarm-cronjob daemon itself.
#
# === AXIS 187 CONTINUES — cron-expression scheduling libraries ============
# Axis position: Go=242 continues Axis 187 (slot 2/0/0).  Canonical Go
# cron-expression scheduler is `github.com/robfig/cron/v3` by Rob
# Figueiredo — the de-facto standard "cron in Go" with classic 5-field
# crontab syntax + Quartz-style 6-field (with seconds) + descriptor
# shorthand (@daily / @hourly / @reboot) + the cron.Schedule
# interface for custom triggers + timezone-aware parsing.  Used by
# Kubernetes' CronJob controller (the integration test that drove
# this library to canonical-status — every k8s user implicitly trusts
# this parser's correctness via the CronJob controller), Argo CD,
# Caddy's reload hooks, and every Go background-job library.
#
# Cycle position in current 3+1 micro-cycle:
#   Rust=242     _cup                 ← previous round (axis 187 OPENS, 1/0/0)
#   Go=242       ← THIS FILE          (axis 187 continues, slot 2/0/0)
#   TS-Node=242  ← next round         (axis 187 CLOSES at triple-242, 1/1/1)
#
# Cross-language design contrast for axis 187:
#   Rust    : tokio-cron-scheduler wraps zslayton/cron (expression
#             parser) + adds async-first runtime + persistent backends
#             (in-memory / SQLite / Postgres / Nats).  Two-layer
#             composition.
#   Go      : robfig/cron is a SINGLE package — expression parser +
#             scheduler + cron.Schedule interface all in one.  Native
#             goroutine concurrency without an explicit runtime
#             dependency.  Persistent storage is left to the consumer
#             (write the schedule + job state to your DB of choice).
#             Reflects Go's preference for unopinionated single-binary
#             building blocks.
#   JS/Node : node-cron OR kelektiv/node-cron — single-package
#             scheduler + parser; pick by ecosystem age.  [TBD next
#             round]
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

_swarm-cronjob() {
    _arguments -s -S \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show CLI help]' \
        '(- *)--version[print version and exit]' \
        '--log-level=[set log level (env LOG_LEVEL, default info)]:level:(trace debug info warn error fatal panic)' \
        '--log-json[enable JSON logging output (env LOG_JSON, default false)]'
}

_swarm-cronjob "$@"
